[{"id":"VR794824","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<p class=\"direction_paragraph\" xmlns=\"http://www.imsglobal.org/xsd/apip/apipv1p0/qtiitem/imsqti_v2p2\" xmlns:xsi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance\"><strong>Part A</strong></p>\n\n<div class=\"item_part part_id:Ai part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"Ai\">\n<ul class=\"unordered_list style:2\">\n\t<li class=\"list_item\">\n\t<p class=\"list_paragraph\">i. <span class=\"formatted_text font_weight:bold\">Derive</span> an expression for the work function of the metal in terms of the wavelength of the light <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"lambda\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"lambda\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>λ</mi></math></span></span>, the maximum speed of the emitted electrons <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"v sub maximum\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"v sub maximum\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>v</mi><mi>max</mi></msub></math></span></span>, and physical constants, as appropriate. Begin your derivation by writing a fundamental physics principle or an equation from the reference information.</p>\n\t</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"item_part part_id:Aii part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"Aii\">\n<ul class=\"unordered_list style:2\">\n\t<li class=\"list_item\">\n\t<p class=\"list_paragraph\">ii. When light of wavelength <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"200 nanometers\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"200 nanometers\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>200</mn><mspace width=\"0.2em\"></mspace><mtext>nm</mtext></math></span></span> shines on the metal, the maximum speed of the emitted electrons is <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"6.5 times 10 to the 5 power, meters per second\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"6.5 times 10 to the 5 power, meters per second\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>6.5</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>5</mn></msup><mspace width=\"0.2em\"></mspace><mtext>m/s</mtext></math></span></span>. <span class=\"formatted_text font_weight:bold\">Calculate</span> the work function of the metal.</p>\n\t</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"item_part part_id:Aiii part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"Aiii\">\n<ul class=\"unordered_list style:2\">\n\t<li class=\"list_item\">\n\t<p class=\"list_paragraph\">iii. The graph in Figure <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"2\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"2\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>2</mn></math></span></span> shows the maximum kinetic energy of the ejected electrons as a function of the frequency of the light for the metal. The original metal is then replaced with a different metal with a greater work function than that of the original metal. On the graph in Figure <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"2\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"2\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>2</mn></math></span></span>, <span class=\"formatted_text font_weight:bold\">sketch</span> a line or curve that could represent the maximum kinetic energy of the electrons as a function of the frequency of the light for the new metal.</p>\n\t</li>\n</ul>\n\n<div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"Figure 2 shows the graph of two line segments in a coordinate plane with the origin labeled O. The horizontal axis is labeled f, the vertical axis is labeled K sub e, and no values are indicated. The first line segment begins at the origin, moves horizontally to the right to a point about halfway along the horizontal axis. The second line segment begins where the first one ends and then moves upward and to the right, ending far above the end of the horizontal axis.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/578/VR794824.g15.svg\" /></div>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"item_part part_id:B part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"B\">\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\">Part B</p>\n\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\">With this new metal, the students find that no electrons are ejected from the metal if they shine red light on the metal. Two students make the following proposals.</p>\n\n<ul class=\"unordered_list style:1\">\n\t<li class=\"list_item\">\n\t<p class=\"list_paragraph\">Student <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"A\"><math alttext=\"A\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math></span></span> proposes that they try using a brighter red light to eject the electrons.</p>\n\t</li>\n\t<li class=\"list_item\">\n\t<p class=\"list_paragraph\">Student <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"B\"><math alttext=\"B\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math></span></span> proposes that they try using green light to eject the electrons.</p>\n\t</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\"><span class=\"formatted_text font_weight:bold\">Indicate</span> which student’s proposal is more likely to produce ejected electrons. <span class=\"formatted_text font_weight:bold\">Justify</span> your answer by referring to both proposals.</p>\n</div>\n","rubricRef":"VR794824_rubric","features":[{"type":"sharedpassage","html":"<p class=\"direction_paragraph\" xmlns=\"http://www.imsglobal.org/xsd/apip/apipv1p0/qtiitem/imsqti_v2p2\" xmlns:xsi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance\">Monochromatic light of wavelength <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"lambda\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"lambda\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>λ</mi></math></span></span> shines on a metal with a work function <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"phi\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"phi\" overflow=\"scroll\"> <mi>ϕ</mi> </math></span></span>, as shown in Figure <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"1\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"1\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>1</mn></math></span></span>. The wavelength of the light is varied, and for some wavelengths electrons are emitted from the metal. The maximum speed <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"v sub maximum\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"v sub maximum\" overflow=\"scroll\"> <msub> <mi>v</mi> <mi>max</mi> </msub> </math></span></span> of the emitted electrons is measured as a function of the wavelength of the light.</p>\n\n<div>\n<div class=\"stimulus_reference\">\n<div class=\"passage\">\n<div class=\"prose style:1\">\n<div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"Figure 1 shows a diagram of a rectangular metal block. Light moves downward and to the right toward the top edge of the metal. Electrons are emitted from the metal. One electron is moving vertically upward and another is moving upward and to the right.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/578/VR794824.g03.svg\" /></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n"}]}]